3 steps to setup git account:

1 : you need to setup your credentials in your system globally using these commands:  
Set a Git username:  
git config \--global user.name "Mona Lisa"

Confirm that you have set the Git username correctly:  
$ git config \--global user.name

* \> Mona Lisa

Set an email address :   
git config \--global user.email "YOUR\_EMAIL"

Confirm that you have set the email address correctly in Git:  
$ git config \--global user.email

* email@example.com

So I need to to setup these , but it says this thing does not connect my computer to the github website/ web server , like yes when I will go git clone or push , it will send request to github and search for account with these credentials which github will will likely find and confirm my local git yes dude I have this guy's account , but it wont let me push code , cause anyone can know my username and email , that does not mean they can now just setup my git in their computer and push random code to my github , they are not that stupid

So that thing that verifies that my computer which is sending the request is the computer that is authorized to send request and the github account whose credentials I have set on my computer belongs to me , I need to generate a ssh key using some algorithm they say and this will generate two file a public and private key , I need to read the public key , copy its text, paste it in my github ssh key section , then there is a command to verify the connected and there you have it  , your git it setup now.

Generate ssh key command: ssh-keygen \-t ed25519 \-C "your\_email@example.com"  
Verify connection : ssh \-T git@github.com

On running verify command if it gives:  
\> Hi USERNAME\! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not  
\> provide shell access.

That means your git is connected to your github account and now you can start using it.

**Ok I was so excited about this idea , so I read on someone blog on twitter about using sqlite3 as a file system , at that time I didn't understand what does that even mean , for me sqlite3 was some wacky db that people use to store small data , I never even used it.**

**But that got me thing about what my requirements were:**  
**\[- Store credentials**  
**\- Execute shell commands to set or unset credentials and generate ssh keys**  
**\- store those ssh keys in proper places(folders)**  
**\- move ssh keys around from key store folder to \~ssh folder based on status of credentials.\]**

**Well what if I stored all the credentials in table rows and their respective ssh file in the db itself , that would solve the issue of storing things in some json of folders and moving files from different folder and to many distributors.**

**What I need is a centrailed distributor , that would be my sqlite3 db** 

**It should look something like this :**   
**![][image2]**

**We will have a table with columns:**  
**user.name , user.email , status , fileBlob**

**So when a user gives us their user.name , user.email , we store this in db and set any previous credentials if they exist.**

**If any previous ssh keys exist , remove them from the \~ssh folder, and generate the new ssh keys and store them as blobs in our db , change the status of the row to ACTIVE.**

**And when a user decides to add a second account , they again give us their user.name , user.email.**

**We store these in the second row of the table , update status of previous row credentials as “INACTIVE”, delete their ssh keys , not move but delete as we already stored them in the db for the first time.**

**Once the \~ssh folder is cleared , we set the credentials of the new row(second row) , generate its ssh keys in \~ssh folder , store them again as blobs, change status of second row as “ACTIVE”**

**So now the first row is inactive and the second row is active , and this same flow/Architecture will be followed so on.**

**I think this is a better way to do things, Sqlite3 is older than when I was even born , written in C , so it works , and freking 3mb dude , TF , how is it possible , I think I understand what they meant when they said sqlite3 is a lightweight file system that you can pack with your application ,** 

**Same commands are used for sqlite3 for windows, mac or linux , so we interact with sqlite3 and it handles the interaction with the file system.**

**So now our core feature to add multiple accounts is now done , the user gives us the user.name and user.email and we handle the rest of the setting of accounts.**

**What next feature do I want :** 

**1 : Add Accounts**  
**2 : Switch Accounts**  
**3 : Delete all accounts**  
**4 : Delete a particular Account**  
**5   Show ssh keys of particular user or all users**  
**6 : List all accounts with their ssh keys and status etc data**

**For these feature I will be using normal database cruds.**

**Adding account we have figured out**

**➕ For switching : When user selects a account that they want to switch to , we unset any previous credentials from system , remove ssh files from \~folder, make status of previous account tha t was active inactive.**

**Then from db we read the credentials of the account we want to switch to , we set those credentials in system , get the ssh keys from there and move them to \~ssh folder , and change status to “ACTIVE” from “INACTIVE”**

**➕ To delete , we will just clean the database by sql commands and remove ssh files from \~ssh folder**

**➕ To delete a particular account , we list down accounts to user , they select one , we goto db delete the row with that user.name and user.email , and if that account’s Status was “ACTIVE” then we clear the \~ssh folder for any ssh keys**

**➕ To show ssh keys for particular user , we show a list of accounts to user , they select one and then we just cat the public ssh keys directly from db and show them the ssh key output**

**➕ TO list all accounts with status , ssh keys , and other data like what account is Active its ssh keys , all accounts details, they ssh keys and status**

**We just use sql queries to read data , ssh files, status and show them in presentable format**
